{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0fb0146a-84b5-454a-89f2-678edc8dd327","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform .NET diagnostic tool.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper OS-level ETW traces, GC analysis |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live triage (`cpu-usage`, `threadpool-queue-length`) before tracing |\n| **dotnet-dump** | If you suspect a tight loop — grab a dump and inspect thread stacks |\n\n### Pro tip — triage first:\n```powershell\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis shows real-time CPU %, GC %, thread pool stats — helps you decide if the issue is CPU-bound code, GC pressure, or thread pool starvation *before* collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e212fa29-4d71-4107-98fd-355f676acdac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no code changes or tool use needed.","outputTokens":369},"id":"b847fcfd-879b-42cd-b44c-e30539a04ff2","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:51:15.960Z","parentId":"08e5e419-bd00-47fe-99e3-ef1ec1527856"}
